Model 1 revealed lower odds ratios (OR) for EBV-IM at older ages and for longer intervals to the first visit, with >40-year-old patients having an OR of 0.13. In contrast, significantly higher ORs for EBV-IM were observed for patients with cervical lymphadenopathy (OR: 11.01) and tonsillar white coat (OR: 4.53). None of the other factors were statistically significant in model 1 (Table 2
). Model 2 revealed a lower OR for EBV-IM at older ages, as well as higher ORs for patients with cervical lymphadenopathy, hepatosplenomegaly, leukocytosis, and atypical lymphocytosis. Interval from onset to visit, tonsillar white coat, and thrombocytopenia were not significant factors in model 2 (Table 3
). Model 3 revealed a lower OR for EBV-IM at older ages, as well as higher ORs for patients with cervical lymphadenopathy, tonsillar white coat, and mild-to-moderate elevations of atypical lymphocytosis (11–30%), LDH (251–500 IU/L), and GGT (51–300 IU/L). Extreme elevations of atypical lymphocytes, LDH and GGT, as well as hepatosplenomegaly, leukocytosis, ALT elevation, and ALP elevation, were not significant factors in model 3 (Table 4
).
